1. Customer Segments in the Intellectual Property (IP) Domain

TCS supports a wide range of organizations that create, manage, protect, and commercialize intellectual property assets. Based on TCS Research & Innovation and TCS Pace™ initiatives, the primary customer segments include:

1.1 Enterprise Organizations

Large enterprises across industries such as banking, healthcare, retail, manufacturing, telecommunications, and energy that require effective management of patents, innovations, trademarks, copyrights, and technology assets.

1.2 Research and Innovation Centers

Organizations engaged in research, invention, and innovation activities that require systems for invention disclosure, patent tracking, and innovation portfolio management.

1.3 Startups and Innovation Ecosystems

Startups, incubators, and innovation partners collaborating with TCS Pace™ to accelerate innovation, validate ideas, and commercialize intellectual assets.

1.4 Academic Institutions and Universities

Universities and research institutions involved in technology development, patent creation, knowledge transfer, and industry-academia collaboration.

1.5 Technology and Product Companies

Organizations developing proprietary technologies, software products, platforms, and digital solutions that require IP protection and commercialization support.

1.6 Innovation and Co-Creation Partners

Industry alliances, consultants, venture partners, and ecosystem collaborators participating in co-innovation and technology development initiatives.

1.7 Government and Public Research Organizations

Public sector institutions and research bodies managing innovation portfolios and intellectual property generated through publicly funded research programs.

2. Internal End Users in an IP Management System

The Intellectual Property Management System is used by multiple internal stakeholders responsible for innovation, patent management, research, and commercialization activities.

2.1 IP Portfolio Managers

Manage patent portfolios, intellectual assets, renewal schedules, technology classifications, and commercialization opportunities.

2.2 Researchers and Inventors

Create inventions, submit invention disclosures, collaborate on innovation projects, and track patent filing progress.

2.3 Research & Innovation Teams

Identify promising ideas, evaluate innovation potential, support patent creation, and manage technology development initiatives.

2.4 Innovation Managers

Monitor innovation pipelines, assess business value, prioritize inventions, and drive strategic innovation programs.

2.5 Legal and Compliance Teams

Handle patent applications, intellectual property filings, licensing agreements, compliance requirements, and legal documentation.

2.6 Technology Transfer and Commercialization Teams

Manage licensing opportunities, royalty agreements, technology partnerships, and commercialization of intellectual property assets.

2.7 Business Unit Leaders

Evaluate innovation performance, review IP portfolios, and align intellectual property investments with business objectives.

2.8 Executive Leadership

Access dashboards and analytics related to innovation metrics, patent portfolios, commercialization outcomes, and strategic decision-making.

2.9 Knowledge Management Teams

Maintain repositories of inventions, patents, research documents, technical disclosures, and organizational knowledge assets.

2.10 System Administrators

Manage user access, workflow configuration, data governance, security controls, and overall system administration.

